Program : 
https://leetcode.com/problems/distinct-subsequences/description/
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Companies : #amazon #barclays #google #mathworks
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Problem : 
Given two strings s and t, return the number of distinct subsequences of s which equals t.

The test cases are generated so that the answer fits on a 32-bit signed integer.

Example 1:

Input: s = "rabbbit", t = "rabbit"
Output: 3
Explanation:
As shown below, there are 3 ways you can generate "rabbit" from s.
rabbbit
rabbbit
rabbbit
Example 2:

Input: s = "babgbag", t = "bag"
Output: 5
Explanation:
As shown below, there are 5 ways you can generate "bag" from s.
babgbag
babgbag
babgbag
babgbag
babgbag
 

Constraints:

1 <= s.length, t.length <= 1000
s and t consist of English letters.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Explanation :

we are using dp approach here ? but why ?
at ith index we have to get the number of sequences happened so far + current possible.

we have source (s) and possible sequence (target - t).
so at each index (i) of t, we will store how many sub sequences possible.

as we have to update current value with the previously occurred sub sequence value.
dp[j]+=dp[j-1] when both current iteration value with the respective (j-1)th value of t.

so if we iterate j from 0 to seq len, if make change for j=2, and when we come to j=3, dp[j-1] will be already changed.
so instead we iterate j from seq len to 0, so we will have both current and prev index value both unchanged.


------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Solution : 

class Solution {
    public int numDistinct(String s, String t) {
        int srcLen = s.length();
        int seqLen = t.length();
        int[] dp = new int[seqLen+1];
        dp[0]=1;
        for(int i=1;i<srcLen+1;i++){
            for(int j=seqLen;j>0;j--){
                if(s.charAt(i-1)==t.charAt(j-1))
                    dp[j]+=dp[j-1];
            }
        }
        return dp[seqLen];        
    }
}
